[[John Buchan|John Buchan, 1st Baron Tweedsmuir]] {{Post-nominals|post-noms=[[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]] [[Order of St Michael and St George|GCMG]] [[Royal Victorian Order|GCVO]] [[Order of the Companions of Honour|CH]]}} (1875&nbsp;– 1940) was a [[List of Scottish novelists|Scottish novelist]], historian, biographer and editor. Outside the field of literature he was, at various times, a barrister, a publisher, a [[Lieutenant colonel (United Kingdom)|lieutenant colonel]] in the [[Intelligence Corps (United Kingdom)|Intelligence Corps]], the Director of Information—reporting directly to prime minister [[David Lloyd George]]—during the First World War and a [[Unionist Party (Scotland)|Unionist]] MP who served as [[Governor General of Canada]], the [[List of Governors General of Canada#Governors General of Canada, 1867–present|15th]] since [[Canadian Confederation]].{{sfn|Matthew|2004}}{{sfn|Daniell|1992|p=4}}<ref name="Times: Obit" />

Born in [[Perth, Scotland|Perth]], Scotland, Buchan was admitted to the [[University of Glasgow]] in 1892 to study classics; during his first year at university he edited the works of [[Francis Bacon]], which were published in 1894.{{sfn|Daniell|1992|p=5}} The following year he was awarded a scholarship to [[Brasenose College, Oxford]]; shortly after his arrival he also published his first novel, ''[[Sir Quixote of the Moors]]'', which he dedicated to [[Gilbert Murray]], his university tutor.{{sfn|MacLeod|1984|p=19}} By the time he left the university he had published five books,{{sfn|Matthew|2004}} including ''Scholar-Gipsies'', the first work of non-fiction he wrote.{{sfn|Daniell|1992|p=4}}<ref name="Guard: Obit" />

Much of Buchan's non-fiction mirrored his circumstances: his time in South Africa resulted in ''The African Colony'', the First World War led to a series of books about the war in general, and the Scottish and South African forces in particular.{{sfn|Daniell|1992|pp=5–6}} He interspersed his non-fiction with further novels, and also wrote ten biographies and four volumes of poetry, as well as numerous articles and stories for magazines and journals.{{sfn|MacLeod|1984|p=19}} During the war he wrote ''[[The Thirty-Nine Steps]]'', the novel which has been adapted for film and television more than any of his other work, (film versions in [[The 39 Steps (1935 film)|1935]]; [[The 39 Steps (1959 film)|1959]]; and [[The Thirty Nine Steps (1978 film)|1978]], as well as a [[The 39 Steps (2008 film)|2008 version for British television]]).{{sfn|MacLeod|1984|p=22}}

